
[1]agony

   AG'ONY, n. [Gr. a contest with bodily exertion; a word used to denote
   the athletic games, in Greece; whence anguish, solicitude; from L. ago.
   Gr. to strive. See Act.]

   1. In strictness, pain so extreme as to cause writhing or contortions
   of the body, similar to those made in the athletic contests in Greece.
   Hence,

   2. Extreme pain of body or mind; anguish; appropriately, the pangs of
   death, and the sufferings of our Savior in the garden of Gethsemane.
   Luke 22.

   3. Violent contest or striving.
